\section{Abstract}

\begin{tcolorbox}[infobox, title={\faInfoCircle\enspace Overview}]
This report presents a systematic \textbf{analysis, simplification, and hardware
implementation} of a digital logic circuit drawn from a GATE Electronics and
Communication Engineering (EC) examination paper. Boolean algebra and DeMorgan's
theorem are applied methodically to reduce the circuit, yielding the result:
\[
  \boxed{Y = 1}
\]
An \textbf{Arduino UNO} platform is subsequently employed to verify this result
experimentally. Three LEDs serve as indicators for the input variables $A$, $B$,
and $C$, while a fourth LED represents the output $Y$. The firmware automatically
iterates through all eight possible input combinations and demonstrates that the
output remains \textsc{HIGH} in every case, thereby confirming the theoretical
derivation.
\end{tcolorbox}

