\subsection{Advantages of Simplification}

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2.2em,
                  label=\textcolor{AccentTeal}{\faArrowRight},
                  itemsep=5pt, topsep=4pt]
  \item \textbf{Complete elimination of hardware} --- all six logic gates are
        removed, replaced by a single connection to V\textsubscript{CC}.
  \item \textbf{Zero propagation delay} --- no gate switching is involved.
  \item \textbf{Reduced power consumption} --- no active logic components draw
        quiescent current.
  \item \textbf{Improved reliability} --- fewer components result in fewer
        potential failure points.
  \item \textbf{Smaller PCB footprint} --- significant area savings in integrated
        circuit layouts and printed circuit board designs.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Conclusion}

\begin{tcolorbox}[infobox, title={\faGraduationCap\enspace Summary}]
The given GATE EC logic circuit was systematically \textbf{analysed and
simplified} using Boolean algebra and DeMorgan's theorem. The final Boolean
expression was found to evaluate to $Y = 1$, establishing that the circuit output
remains at logic HIGH for every possible combination of inputs, rendering the
underlying gate network functionally redundant.

An \textbf{Arduino UNO} based implementation was subsequently developed and
tested. The experimental observations were in complete agreement with the
theoretical analysis. This project underscores the practical significance of
\textbf{Boolean simplification} and \textbf{logic optimisation} in reducing
hardware cost, minimising power consumption, and streamlining design complexity
in digital electronic systems.
\end{tcolorbox}

